<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>CEO Pay in Charities</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written Evidence from Simon Gerry [CEP0005]</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I just wanted to put forward a few thoughts relating to the pay of Chief Executives in Charities.  I joined the charity sector 6 years ago following a career in the military and a post in the Ministry of Defence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relating to specifically to pay and pensions.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> I am currently the CEO of a medium sized charity in the education sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Two key messages:</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.05pt; padding-left:22.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I urge the committee to leave the Boards of charities to determine the pay of CEOs; they are the best infor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">med and best placed to make informed decisions, and have legal responsibilities to act prudently and in the interests of the charity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.56pt; padding-left:22.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Introducing artificial caps of any kind would do irreparable damage to the sector and the contribution it makes to social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">good and the wider society.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Thoughts</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There has been a lot in the press recently about CEO/Senior Manager pay and the possible introduction of some kind of capped or ratio formula based upon the minimum pay grade and the maximum pay grade.  Whilst I am v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ery conscious of the pressures facing many people in relatively low paid roles and the subsequent public concern about how funds in all organisations are expended care needs to be taken to ensure that charities remain strong, well led and effectively gover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ned.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There has been an evident improvement across the charity sector in terms of governance leadership and going about things in a much more business- like fashion, and this is because leaders with the correct skills, values and attitudes have been attr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">acted to the sector.  As a consequence the overall social impact created has increased and the sector is very well placed to help face the challenges of delivering more for less over the coming years.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">What I have learnt since</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being in the sector is that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the charity sector is too diverse to apply consistent rules to in terms of pay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and from experience politicians in Whitehall don’t seem to recognise the complexities involved.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pay should be determined in line with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">responsibilities undertaken and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">market need and cannot be capped or related to a maximum v minimum ratio.  This would not take into account the management of resources or people, whether that be public or donated funds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or they be staff or volunteers.  You may have a relatively small st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aff base but a lot of responsibility in awarding legacy grants or funding, or you may have a relatively small income but be managing thousands of volunteers.  Whilst in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private sector comparing the salaries of two major banking CEOs, or in the public s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ector those of two local council CEOs similar comparators can be found, this would be much more difficult in the charity sector.  I also believe that if you did look at the very big national charities (and I am not in that bracket, nor likely to be) the re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sponsibility of the CEO and the salary granted would be well below that of their comparators in the private sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with similar responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and more than likely less than the public sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In essence, my message is that if the public wanted to st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">op donating to a particular charity because of a highly paid CEO then they could do so and that is their choice; ultimately as an extreme example the charity may reduce in size </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as a result </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CEO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pay reduced accordingly as there would be less to manag</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and less responsibility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">!  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When looking at charities that provide public services, the salaries are always likely to be less than private providers who are also considered to commission the contracts awarded.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ACEVO do some good </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on pay and this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> informs many pay and remuneration committees; certainly my Board consider their findings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as well as other similar organisations to ours</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> when reviewing my own remuneration and that is rightly so.  As long as the reporting requirements ensure that pay conti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nues to be transparent then it should be left alone.  To artificially cap pay could lead to an exodus of some very talented people doing some very good work in the sector, and that would be detrimental to the charities themselves, and the overall economy i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the skills to maximise social good are not retained.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I urge the committee to l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eave the Boards of charities to determine the pay of CEOs; they are the best informed and best placed to make informed decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and have legal responsibilities to act pruden</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tly and in the interests of the charity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>